      "writtenOn": "2021-03-12T17:31:18Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "So I guess we\u0027re not trying to catch cases like \"int a \u003d 1; a \u003d 2;\" (with no further refs to \u0027a\u0027) -  this would be a dead variable, but won\u0027t be caught by this code. We clearly do eliminate \"int a \u003d 1;\" - does \"int a; a \u003d 1;\" get caught?\n\nIf I\u0027m reading the code right, it seems like it wouldn\u0027t be eliminated, but it would pass this check and make it into the full scan - which is unnecessary, because we already know that it won\u0027t pass. We could check whether it has an initial value and change the threshold on the number of writes in this test to match; should let us skip some unnecessary scans.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 650,
        "startChar": 57,
        "endLine": 650,
        "endChar": 75
      },
      "revId": "eaea82b49773f2546ef3fb0e80169ac25c1e58f8",
